{{Refimprove|date=August 2017}}
'''The Cateys''' are a UK award ceremony for the hospitality industry, first held in 1984. They have been described as the hospitality industry's equivalent of the Oscars. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/restaurants/florians-2-review-crouch-end-is-cool-again-thanks-to-an-italian-comeback-a3890036.html|title=Evening Standard - Fay Maschler reviews Florian 2|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/jersey/4582465.stm|title=BBC News - World - Europe - Jersey - Michelin restaurant up for award|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/bbcworldwide/worldwidestories/pressreleases/2003/01_january/gary_rhodes_at_the_table.shtml|title=BBC - Worldwide Press Office - Gary Rhodes At The Table|website=BBC|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/811818.stm|title=BBC News - Entertainment - Emmerdale's Mandy to bow out|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> Recipients are nominated, selected and awarded by the industry through [[The Caterer]] magazine.
The Chef Award is one of the most coveted and previous winners include [[Claude Bosi]] in 2018, [[Tom Kerridge]] in 2017, [[Jason Atherton]] in 2012, [[Angela Hartnett]] in 2009, [[Heston Blumenthal]] in 2004, [[Gordon Ramsay]] in 2000, [[Brian Turner (chef)|Brian Turner]] in 1997 and [[Raymond Blanc]] in 1990.
November 2007 saw the first spin-off event, The Hotel Cateys, which took place at the London Hilton on Park Lane, with Grant Hearn, CEO of Travelodge, taking the inaugural Outstanding Contribution to the Industry Award.
The Foodservice Cateys launched in 2013 at Park Plaza Westminster Bridge.
